The paper discusses privacy in communication protocols, which is a topic closely related to computer security (cs.CR). The paper also introduces a connection between the approximate privacy framework and computational geometry, which suggests a possible fit for the paper in the data structures (cs.DS) or information theory (cs.IT) categories. The paper also involves calculations of privacy approximation ratios, which could be considered as a computational complexity (cs.CC) or machine learning (cs.LG) problem.
